According to the National Peanut Board, the average American child will eat 1,500 peanut butter and jelly sandwiches by the time he or she graduates from high school.

Americans eat enough peanut butter in a year - a total of 1.5billion pounds - to make more than 10billion PB&J sandwiches to the tune of $800million.

The peanut butter sandwich has been around since the Great Depression, when cash-strapped families who could not afford meat turned to the humble legume as a cheap substitute for protein.

