But it was not until World War II that the PB&J sandwich we know today became a beloved staple, as both jelly and the high-protein peanut butter were part of the soldiers' rations, along with pre-sliced white bread.

After V-Day, PB&J sales skyrockets in the U.S. thanks to returning GIs who helped popularize the treat, making it a favorite with children and adults alike. 

